{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516056"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:38:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:38:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12553"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12553"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.19,0.28,0.04,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5052"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111346"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5052"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12553"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93475"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2149"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"5591"},{"type":"tags","id":"5617"},{"type":"tags","id":"5620"},{"type":"tags","id":"5621"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8404"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8420"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34578"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35197"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35206"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36148"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40366"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41822"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45277"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111346"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the post-anaesthesia care unit following a laparoscopic cholecystectomy under general anaesthesia. He has a history of hypertension and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. His regular medications include amlodipine and salbutamol inhaler.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring the procedure, the patient was paralysed for intubation and received standard anaesthetic agents. After surgery, he was extubated and prepared for transfer. Soon after extubation, he remains drowsy in recovery. On examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 92/min, blood pressure 138/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 12/min, SpO2 92% on six litres of oxygen via Hudson mask, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Pupils are mid-sized and reactive. There are no rashes, facial swelling, or muscle rigidity. Chest auscultation reveals reduced breath sounds at the bases without wheeze.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s respiratory compromise?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Opioid overdose","Atelectasis","Incomplete reversal of neuromuscular blockade","Bronchospasm","Aspiration pneumonitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAtelectasis is a common postoperative complication, particularly after abdominal surgery. It occurs due to alveolar collapse from factors including general anaesthesia, recumbency, pain-related shallow breathing, and in laparoscopic procedures, the effects of pneumoperitoneum on diaphragmatic function. It is important to note that patients emerging from general anaesthesia may have reduced respiratory rates due to residual effects of anaesthetic agents, though rates below eight per minute warrant concern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtelectasis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause in this scenario. The patient has low oxygen saturation, reduced breath sounds at the bases, and a history of recent laparoscopic surgery, which increases the risk of atelectasis due to pneumoperitoneum, recumbency, and impaired diaphragmatic movement. Atelectasis is a common cause of postoperative hypoxaemia, especially after abdominal surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpioid overdose\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with marked hypoventilation (often respiratory rate less than eight per minute), unresponsiveness, and pinpoint pupils. In this case, the respiratory rate is 12/min, which is within normal limits for a patient recovering from anaesthesia, and the pupils are mid-sized and reactive, making opioid toxicity less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncomplete reversal of neuromuscular blockade\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely here, as the patient was able to be extubated and there is no mention of profound muscle weakness or inability to maintain airway or ventilation. Incomplete reversal usually presents with significant muscle weakness and ventilatory failure, which is not described in this case. With the increasing use of sugammadex as a reversal agent for rocuronium and vecuronium, incomplete reversal of neuromuscular blockade has become less common compared to when neostigmine was the primary reversal agent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchospasm\u003C/strong\u003E would be expected to present with wheeze and increased work of breathing, particularly in a person with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. The absence of wheeze and the presence of reduced breath sounds at the bases make this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspiration pneumonitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause hypoxaemia and respiratory distress postoperatively, but is usually associated with cough, coarse crackles, or evidence of aspiration during or after extubation. There is no mention of these findings in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPostoperative hypoxaemia is common and multifactorial. Careful assessment of clinical features and risk factors is essential to guide appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Atelectasis is a frequent cause of postoperative hypoxaemia, particularly after abdominal surgery.","Incomplete reversal of muscle relaxants typically presents with profound muscle weakness and inability to maintain airway or ventilation.","Clinical features such as respiratory rate, oxygen saturation, and examination findings help differentiate causes of postoperative respiratory compromise."],"references":["Singh R, Sadiq NM. Cholinesterase Inhibitors. [Updated 2022 Jul 18]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK544336/","Arzanipour G, Heitz JW. Hypoxia. In: Heitz JW, editor. Post-Anesthesia Care: Symptoms, Diagnosis and Management. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press; 2016. p. 66\u201373."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93475"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12553"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93475"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-12T21:11:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-12T21:11:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5052"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111346"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"20